div.div: Docker should be successfully setup on our module, we've created the github action to ensure that it builds automatically when pushing to our main branch. This issue will now be closed.

Updated to Paul's docker-image.yml
Accompanied by @Wilhaz

Merge pull request #3 from BUAdvDev2024/feature/api
API Integration

Configured docker to run correctly with our file structure
Updated our Dockerfile to reflect our project structure. Verified that it builds and runs correctly under the new file changes.

Added a debug admin page
Added a debug admin page to view and control all orders in the database. This will only be available whilst testing and will include basic CRUD features

Add encryption for data using Fernet encryption
Implemented Fernet encryption for sensitive data. I've added functions to encrypt and decrypt data before storing and retrieving them from the database. All relevant functions have been updated to accommodate for the new security.

Added unit TESTING to each possible action in the routes.py file
Included a new tests.py file to run test actions for each route specified in our routes file. We're running every expected "invalid" test and comparing the returned value to the expected value.
This will be ran anytime we make a change to the pre-existing route system.

Added Amend Items and Delete Items Function
Added an Amend Items function that allows a specific order to have it's corresponding items updated (all at once for now) whereby corresponding items to an order_id are wiped and replaced with new ones.
This incentivised a new function called "delete_order_items" whereby items tied to a specific Order ID are deleted. This has multiple uses.

Added an Update Status Route with Restful Architecture
Added a new Route for Updating an Order Status within a specified Order.
This can be utilised by Kitchen and waiter staff to update specific order's from 'PENDING' to 'IN-PROGRESS' to 'COMPLETE' depending on their preferences from other sub-systems.
The main call takes the Order ID as an argument and the New Status as a payload (subject to review) and utilises a route further from the Order ID to a "status" change route (for specificity)

Added a way to view existing orders and their items
Included another route that allows you to specify an order id to view an order that exists, this shows you the order, the order's status, it's ID as well as the items linked to it.

Added API authorization check using headers
I am now checking whether the inbound POST request includes an authorisation header, and if that header includes the correct API key. This adds a level of security so that any unauthorised users cannot use our API. The API key is a random 32 bit string consisting of alphanumerical characters.

Reconfigured the API to adhere to RESTful principles
The API now adheres to RESTful principles as i've implemented a resource based URL ("/orders"). I've also sorted the appropriate code into functions and generated docstrings accordingly.

Started API Work - Create Order with Items
Started a new Routes.py file that can process a new create_order_with_items command for Flask utilising blueprints.
This command will initialise a new order within the database with a given userID and itemList.
Most errors it encounters will be returned as suitable JSON error formats encoded with the reason the error occurred.
Docstrings will be attached to the code once sampled and verified by @notsceptor to be working as intended.
